,"id":"35245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41933"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107665"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department via ambulance after his housemate was concerned about his wellbeing. The patient has been profusely sweating and shaking over the course of the day, and has been troubled by \u0022little creatures\u0022 running around the room. He is recently unemployed, having been fired due to intoxication with several substances \u2013 although this triggered him to cease using. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears anxious and diffusely diaphoretic. His pulse rate is 112/min, blood pressure 148/92 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.7\u00b0C. Pupils are 3 mm and reactive, mucous membranes are moist and bowel sounds are present. There is an intention tremor of the upper limbs but no myoclonus or clonus. Neurological examination is otherwise normal, though he is disoriented to place.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pharmacological agents is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haloperidol","Diazepam","Thiamine","Physostigmine","Naloxone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of tremor, autonomic hyperactivity, low-grade fever and visual hallucinations is highly suggestive of alcohol withdrawal. Withdrawal typically begins within six to 48 hours from the last drink, with risk of delirium tremens increasing from 48 hours of sobriety lasting up to 96 hours. In this case, whilst the patient denies any substance abuse, there are other indicators of underlying substance misuse such as recent unemployment due to intoxication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is the drug of choice for acute alcohol withdrawal. A long-acting benzodiazepine controls agitation, mitigates autonomic overactivity and prevents progression to seizures or delirium tremens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E can reduce severe psychosis or agitation but does not treat the underlying hyperexcitable state of alcohol withdrawal and, used alone, may lower the seizure threshold.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiamine\u003C/strong\u003E is an important adjunct in alcohol withdrawal to prevent Wernicke encephalopathy, but it does not treat the acute withdrawal syndrome itself. It should be given alongside benzodiazepines but is not the most appropriate initial treatment for the acute symptoms. In addition, this patient is not currently exhibiting any signs of symptoms of Wenicke\u0027s. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysostigmine\u003C/strong\u003E reverses central anticholinergic toxicity characterised by dry skin, mydriasis, urinary retention and absent bowel sounds. The presence of sweating, moist mucous membranes and normal bowel sounds argues against an anticholinergic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaloxone\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for opioid toxicity, which presents with central nervous system depression, bradypnoea and miosis. The current picture of agitation, tremor, hypertension and fever is incompatible with opioid overdose.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alcohol withdrawal usually begins 6\u201348 hours after the last drink and presents with tremor, autonomic hyperactivity and perceptual disturbance.","A long-acting benzodiazepine such as diazepam is first-line because it treats agitation and prevents progression to seizures or delirium tremens.","Other toxidromes (anticholinergic, cholinergic, opioid) have distinguishing examination findings and require different, specific antidotes."],"references":["Jonas DE, Amick HR, Feltner C, Bobashev G, Thomas K, Wines R, Kim MM, Shanahan E, Gass CE, Rowe CJ, Garbutt JC. Pharmacotherapy for adults with alcohol use disorders in outpatient settings: a systematic review and meta-analysis. JAMA. 2014 May 14;311(18):1889-900. doi: 10.1001/jama.2014.3628. PMID: 24825644.","DSM-5 criteria for alcohol use disorder: https://cchealth.org/aod/pdf/DSM-5%20Diagnosis%20Reference%20Guide.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90097"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2641"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90097"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T20:51:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T20:52:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2641"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107665"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name"